&lt;hr /&gt;

&lt;h1 id=&#34;voice-conversion-based-anonymization&#34;&gt;Voice conversion based anonymization&lt;/h1&gt;

&lt;hr /&gt;

&lt;h2 id=&#34;relevance&#34;&gt;Relevance&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Logical speaker anonymization framework

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;fragment &#34; &gt;
Convert &lt;span style=&#34;color: #31B404&#34;&gt;source&lt;/span&gt; speaker&amp;rsquo;s voice to a &lt;span style=&#34;color: #31B404&#34;&gt;target&lt;/span&gt; speaker
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;fragment &#34; &gt;
Choice of &lt;span style=&#34;color: #31B404&#34;&gt;target&lt;/span&gt; speaker is critical for strength of anonymization
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;fragment &#34; &gt;
Allows data publication
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;fragment &#34; &gt;
First proposed in 2009 [2], many techniques proposed thereafter.
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;hr /&gt;

&lt;h2 id=&#34;three-vc-methods&#34;&gt;Three VC methods&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;p&gt;VC methods are selected based on the following criteria:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Non-parallel&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Many-to-many&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Source/language independent&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;hr /&gt;

&lt;h2 id=&#34;three-vc-methods-1&#34;&gt;Three VC methods&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;fragment &#34; &gt;
&lt;span style=&#34;color: #EF7A7A&#34;&gt;VoiceMask&lt;/span&gt;: simple frequency warping based on composition of two functions $B$ and $Q$: $ f&amp;rsquo; = B(Q(f, \alpha), \beta) $
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;fragment &#34; &gt;
&lt;span style=&#34;color: #EF7A7A&#34;&gt;Vocal Tract Length Normalization&lt;/span&gt;: learn transformation parameters between source and target class spectra.
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;fragment &#34; &gt;
&lt;span style=&#34;color: #EF7A7A&#34;&gt;Disentangled Speech Representation&lt;/span&gt;: Separate encoders for &lt;strong&gt;content&lt;/strong&gt; (instance normalization) and &lt;strong&gt;speaker&lt;/strong&gt; (average pooling) information.
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;hr /&gt;

